metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #86
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Pages From A Redacted Document #49
metadata.description:
In a time of mistrust, fear and corruption this work looks to reflect how transparency and accountability are removed from those with responsibility with a simple black line.

An abstract representation of the murky world that lurks behind the corridors of power. Kept there hidden and away from the masses.  We demand more.

A representation of documents printed and hand written, that are augmented with highlighters and blocking out pens.

press 'S' to download the hi-res version, which will show the full detail.

metadata.name: Almost #79
metadata.description:
Hello, I am a 13-year-old girl who has put together this image-composition project for my project-based-learning end-of-term project.  This term we learned about biodiversity and how biodiversity loss affects us and the world around us.  All the images in this project are hand-drawn (on an iPad) by me.

I will be donating all proceeds from the minting of this project to plant trees.  Secondary royalties will be kept by me.  Thank you all ahead of time for your support!

metadata.name: NAZCA #91
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

👽 Kim Asendorf

metadata.name: SWTBD - London Prototype #61
metadata.description:
Several ways to break down - London Prototype is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022

A generative geometry systems exploring broken things by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut

mouse:

click: toggle active mode. In active mode, a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features is generated every 10s.

keyboard:

'a' or 'A' : add a slice or point, depending on mode
's' or 'S' : add a slice, regardless of mode
'c' or 'C' : cut mesh along view
'e': decrease explosion factor
'E': increase explosion factor
'r' or 'R': create a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features
'v' or 'V': switch view
   '1': Render view
   '2': Point/ plane view
   '3': Slice view
   '4': Construction view
   '5': Mesh view

'+' and '-': zoom in and out
arrow keys: rotate around and translate along the vertical axis

metadata.name: Disjoint and Disoriented #65
metadata.description:
Disjoint and Disoriented is about the abstract structure formed by the equalities and oppositions of its parts.

It might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop is recommended.

There are three render options available as url parameters in live mode:
- size=XXXX (up to 5760 pixels)
- texture=0 (disable canvas texture for print)
- shader=1 (use the shader throughout the painting process, can be heavy)

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi and lunarean, 2022.

metadata.name: partition() #400
metadata.description:
This token continuously partitions the canvas, sometimes taking minutes to create tens of thousands of subdivisions. Each token has unique properties that govern partition number and shape, and a random chance to freeze a partition. This allows for a wide variety of outputs, all driven by pure randomness.

Properties describe the entropy of the final output, the final number of partitions, and a rare small chance for filled partitions. This token also has a few interactive features as well (see below).

Software | p5.js
Created  | 11/30/21
Artist   | nicthib

Controls:
1-9: Displays the construction of the piece at each iteration
p: Save a png of the current canvas
s: Save an svg of the current canvas (Note: this can break the live sketch, so reload the page if you want to interact further)
Space: Resets animation
Scroll, click/drag: zoom/pan

metadata.name: the Glory of Colours #184
metadata.description:
According to Kandinsky, painting “can create the same energies in the observer that music can make in the listener. The abstract painter is an echo seeker: just like the relationship between music and the listener, shapes and colors must penetrate the observer's soul. They vibrate the threads of his existence and resonate in the depths of his mind, you can still find references to people, buildings, mountains, etc., but these are more signs than manifestations. They do not evoke objects but abstractly reveal them, like the simplified image we have seen before of objects and elements in nature.
Classical philosophy reinforces the belief that existing, tangible reality is a mask for a deeper reality that can only be reached through imagination. I have tried to combine this with the art of coding and creating canvases of millions of characters and numbers.
Made in p5js
Created July 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi

metadata.name: The Foggy Trees #71
metadata.description:
This is the second project exploring the possibilities of fictional trees. I used only two elements, the sun and the trees, to outline the whole picture.

There are 7 kinds of total number of trees (between 1 and 34 of Fibonacci series). Each generative token have one of three fork rates, giving the trees a different look. Finally, in addition to the no tint ones, there are 6 tint colors to give them different vibes.

Made with p5js.

Please follow me on Twitter: luyotw

Controls:
- Press “f” to toggle the frame, there is my signature on the mat inside the frame.
- Press “s” to save the image displayed at that moment.

metadata.name: Bardez #96
metadata.description:
Bardez is the Armenian word for garden. It is etymologically tied to an ancient word for paradise, but that link goes deeper than etymology. Gardens have always been small pieces of paradise for me, and hearing the word in Armenian triggers a flood of warm memories.

Memories of wandering around my grandfather’s garden, plucking ripe plums and figs from their branches.
Memories of playing in my parents yard, the scent of jasmine in the summer heat.
Of sun warmed tomatoes in my mom’s vegetable patch.
The smell of dirt and grass.
Mud on my hands.
Sun on my skin.
Memories of paradise.

I hope you enjoy these gardens I’ve planted, and I hope they remind you of some warm and wonderful memories.
 
Nat Sarkissian






Notes:
 - This piece uses a shader to compute the lighting of the terrain in the first frame. If you don’t have a graphics card, you may have difficulty running this.

 - Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you the progress of the render, and also show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

 - Finally, collectors at the highest tier will be entitled to a signed print of their edition. For further details and updates, keep an eye on my Twitter (@_NatSarkissian).

metadata.name: KoP.003 Studies Series #1
metadata.description:
Kingdom of Peripatetica (KoP.003 Studies Series) explores the creation of a world constructed of segmented, soft-body primitives. In this piece, open and closed frames float in a mirrored room controlled by hidden forces, including: gravity, wind, turbulence and rigid spheres.

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
Mouse Rt Btn -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
f, g: - | + gravity
e, w: east-west wind 
n, s: north-south wind
<, >: reduce | increase turbulence
-, +: remove | add sphere
r: reset dynamics


Note:
Please post your favorite KoP.003 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node
